rmativity of logic to an application of Peirce’s semiotics to John Coltrane’s “A Love Supreme.” A recurrent question throughout is whether a moral theory can be grounded in Peirce’s work, despite his rather vehement denial that this can be done. Some essays ask whether a dichotomy exists between theoretical and practical ethics. Other essays show that Peirce’s philosophy embraces meliorism, examine the role played by self-control, seek to ground communication theory in Peirce’s speculative rhetoric, or examine the normative aspect of the notion of truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aBergman, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColapietro, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiszka, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayorga, Rosa Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOleksy, Mateusz W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPape, Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Kelly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPietarinen, Ahti-Veikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPihlström, Sami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedondo, Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkowroski, Krysztof Piotr, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWaal, Cornelis De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ade Waal, Cornelis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2